[src:pyarrow-python/apache-arrow] Arrow can be used with Apache Parquet, Apache Spark, NumPy, PySpark, pandas and other data processing libraries.
[src:pyarrow-python/apache-arrow] The project includes native software libraries written in C, C++, C#, Go, Java, JavaScript, Julia, MATLAB, Python (PyArrow), R, Ruby, and Rust.
[src:pyarrow-python/apache-arrow] Arrow allows for zero-copy reads and fast data access and interchange without serialization overhead between these languages and systems.
[src:pyarrow-python/apache-arrow] Arrow has been used in diverse domains, including analytics, genomics, and cloud computing.
[src:pyarrow-python/apache-arrow] Apache Parquet and Apache ORC are popular examples of on-disk columnar data formats.
[src:pyarrow-python/apache-arrow] Arrow is designed as a complement to these formats for processing data in-memory.
[src:pyarrow-python/apache-arrow] The hardware resource engineering trade-offs for in-memory processing vary from those associated with on-disk storage.
[src:pyarrow-python/apache-arrow] The Arrow and Parquet projects include libraries that allow for reading and writing data between the two formats.
[src:pyarrow-python/apache-arrow] Apache Arrow was announced by The Apache Software Foundation on February 17, 2016, with development led by a coalition of developers from other open source data analytics projects.
[src:pyarrow-python/apache-arrow] The initial codebase and Java library was seeded by code from Apache Drill.
[src:pyarrow-python/apache-parquet] The open-source project to build Apache Parquet began as a joint effort between Twitter and Cloudera using the record shredding and assembly algorithm as described in Google's Dremel.
[src:pyarrow-python/apache-parquet] Parquet was designed as an improvement on the Trevni columnar storage format created by Doug Cutting, the creator of Hadoop.
[src:pyarrow-python/apache-parquet] 'small compartment') refers to a style of decorative flooring and was chosen to "evoke the bottom layer of a database with an interesting layout".
[src:pyarrow-python/apache-parquet] The first version, Apache Parquet 1.0, was released in July 2013.
[src:pyarrow-python/apache-parquet] Since April 27, 2015, Apache Parquet has been a top-level Apache Software Foundation (ASF)-sponsored project.
[src:pyarrow-python/apache-parquet] Apache Parquet is implemented using the record-shredding and assembly algorithm, which accommodates the complex data structures that can be used to store data.
[src:pyarrow-python/apache-parquet] Apache Parquet is implemented using the Apache Thrift framework, which increases its flexibility; it can work with a number of programming languages like C++, Java, Python, PHP, etc.
[src:pyarrow-python/apache-parquet] As of August 2015, Parquet supports the big-data-processing frameworks including Apache Hive, Apache Drill, Apache Impala, Apache Crunch, Apache Pig, Cascading, Presto and Apache Spark.
[src:pyarrow-python/apache-parquet] It is one of the external data formats used by the pandas Python data manipulation and analysis library.
[src:pyarrow-python/apache-parquet] In Parquet, compression is performed column by column, which enables different encoding schemes to be used for text and integer data.
[src:pyarrow-python/apache-parquet] This strategy also keeps the door open for newer and better encoding schemes to be implemented as they are invented.
[src:pyarrow-python/apache-parquet] Parquet supports various compression formats: snappy, gzip, LZO, brotli, zstd, and LZ4.
[src:pyarrow-python/apache-parquet] Parquet has an automatic dictionary encoding enabled dynamically for data with a *small* number of unique values (i.e. below 105) that enables significant compression and boosts processing speed.
[src:pyarrow-python/apache-parquet] Storage of integers is usually done with dedicated 32 or 64 bits per integer.
[src:pyarrow-python/apache-parquet] For small integers, packing multiple integers into the same space makes storage more efficient.
[src:pyarrow-python/apache-parquet] To optimize storage of multiple occurrences of the same value, run-length encoding is used, which is where a single value is stored once along with the number of occurrences.
[src:pyarrow-python/apache-parquet] Parquet implements a hybrid of bit packing and RLE, in which the encoding switches based on which produces the best compression results.
[src:pyarrow-python/apache-parquet] This strategy works well for certain types of integer data and combines well with dictionary encoding.
[src:pyarrow-python/apache-parquet] Parquet is widely used as the underlying file format in modern cloud-based data lake architectures.
[src:pyarrow-python/apache-parquet] Cloud storage systems such as Amazon S3, Azure Data Lake Storage, and Google Cloud Storage commonly store data in Parquet format due to its efficient columnar representation and retrieval capabilities.
[src:pyarrow-python/apache-parquet] Data lakehouse frameworks—including Apache Iceberg, Delta Lake, and Apache Hudi —build an additional metadata layer on top of Parquet files to support features such as schema evolution, time-travel queries, and ACID-compliant transactions.
[src:pyarrow-python/apache-parquet] In these architectures, Parquet files serve as the immutable storage layer while the table formats manage data versioning and transactional integrity.
[src:pyarrow-python/apache-parquet] Apache Parquet is comparable to RCFile and Optimized Row Columnar (ORC) file formats — all three fall under the category of columnar data storage within the Hadoop ecosystem.
[src:pyarrow-python/apache-parquet] They all have better compression and encoding with improved read performance at the cost of slower writes.
[src:pyarrow-python/apache-parquet] In addition to these features, Apache Parquet supports limited schema evolution, i.e., the schema can be modified according to the changes in the data.
[src:pyarrow-python/apache-parquet] It also provides the ability to add new columns and merge schemas that do not conflict.
[src:pyarrow-python/apache-parquet] Apache Arrow is designed as an in-memory complement to on-disk columnar formats like Parquet and ORC.
[src:pyarrow-python/apache-parquet] The Arrow and Parquet projects include libraries that allow for reading and writing between the two formats.
[src:pyarrow-python/column-oriented-dbms] The choice of data orientation is a trade-off and an architectural decision in databases, query engines, and numerical simulations.
[src:pyarrow-python/column-oriented-dbms] As a result of these tradeoffs, row-oriented formats are more commonly used in online transaction processing (OLTP) and column-oriented formats are more commonly used in online analytical processing (OLAP).
[src:pyarrow-python/column-oriented-dbms] Examples of column-oriented formats include Apache ORC, Apache Parquet, Apache Arrow, formats used by BigQuery, Amazon Redshift and Snowflake.
[src:pyarrow-python/column-oriented-dbms] Predominant examples of row-oriented formats include CSV, formats used in most relational databases (Oracle, MySQL etc.), the in-memory format of Apache Spark, and Apache Avro.
[src:pyarrow-python/column-oriented-dbms] Tabular data is two dimensional — data is modeled as rows and columns.
[src:pyarrow-python/column-oriented-dbms] However, computer systems represent data in a linear memory model, both in-disk and in-memory.
[src:pyarrow-python/column-oriented-dbms] Therefore, a table in a linear memory model requires mapping its two-dimensional scheme into a one-dimensional space.
[src:pyarrow-python/column-oriented-dbms] Data orientation is to the decision taken in this mapping.
[src:pyarrow-python/column-oriented-dbms] There are two prominent mappings: row-oriented and column-oriented.
[src:pyarrow-python/column-oriented-dbms] I.e. each row of the table is located one after the other.
[src:pyarrow-python/column-oriented-dbms] In this orientation, values in the same row are close in space (e.g. similar address in an addressable space).
[src:pyarrow-python/column-oriented-dbms] I.e. each column of the table is located one after the other.
[src:pyarrow-python/column-oriented-dbms] In this orientation, values on the same column are close in space (e.g. similar address in an addressable space).
[src:pyarrow-python/column-oriented-dbms] See list of column-oriented DBMSes for more examples.
[src:pyarrow-python/column-oriented-dbms] Data orientation is an important architectural decision of systems handling data because it results in important tradeoffs in performance and storage.
[src:pyarrow-python/column-oriented-dbms] Below are selected dimensions of this tradeoff.
[src:pyarrow-python/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast random access of rows.
[src:pyarrow-python/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast random access of columns.
[src:pyarrow-python/column-oriented-dbms] In both cases, this is the result of fewer page or cache misses when accessing the data.
[src:pyarrow-python/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast insertion of a new row.
[src:pyarrow-python/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast insertion of a new column.
[src:pyarrow-python/column-oriented-dbms] This dimension is an important reason why row-oriented formats are more commonly used in online transaction processing (OLTP), as it results in faster transactions in comparison to column-oriented.
[src:pyarrow-python/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast access under a filter.
[src:pyarrow-python/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast access under a projection.
[src:pyarrow-python/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast analytics operations.
[src:pyarrow-python/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of being able to leverage SIMD instructions.
[src:pyarrow-python/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from smaller uncompressed size.
[src:pyarrow-python/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of the possibility that this orientation offers to represent certain data types with dedicated encodings.
[src:pyarrow-python/column-oriented-dbms] For example, a table of 128 rows with a Boolean column requires 128 bytes in a row-oriented format (one byte per Boolean) but 128 bits (16 bytes) in a column-oriented format (via a bitmap).
[src:pyarrow-python/column-oriented-dbms] Another example is the use of run-length encoding to encode a column.
[src:pyarrow-python/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from smaller compressed size.
[src:pyarrow-python/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of a higher homogeneity within a column than within multiple rows.
[src:pyarrow-python/column-oriented-dbms] Because both orientations represent the same data, it is possible to convert a row-oriented dataset to a column-oriented dataset and vice versa at the expense of compute.
[src:pyarrow-python/column-oriented-dbms] In particular, advanced query engines often leverage each orientation's advantages, and convert from one orientation to the other as part of their execution.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] A **data model** is an abstract model that organizes elements of data and standardizes how they relate to one another and to the properties of real-world entities.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] For instance, a data model may specify that the data element representing a car be composed of a number of other elements which, in turn, represent the color and size of the car and define its owner.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] The corresponding professional activity is called generally *data modeling* or, more specifically, *database design*.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Data models are typically specified by a data expert, data specialist, data scientist, data librarian, or a data scholar.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] A data modeling language and notation are often represented in graphical form as diagrams.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] A data model can sometimes be referred to as a data structure, especially in the context of programming languages.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Data models are often complemented by function models, especially in the context of enterprise models.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] A data model explicitly determines the *structure of data*; conversely, **structured data** is data organized according to an explicit data model or data structure.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Structured data is in contrast to *unstructured data* and *semi-structured data*.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] The term ***data model*** can refer to two distinct but closely related concepts.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Sometimes it refers to an abstract formalization of the objects and relationships found in a particular application domain: for example the customers, products, and orders found in a manufacturing organization.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] At other times it refers to the set of concepts used in defining such formalizations: for example concepts such as entities, attributes, relations, or tables.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] So the "data model" of a banking application may be defined using the entity–relationship "data model".
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] This article uses the term in both senses.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Managing large quantities of structured and unstructured data is a primary function of information systems.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Data models describe the structure, manipulation, and integrity aspects of the data stored in data management systems such as relational databases.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] They may also describe data with a looser structure, such as word processing documents, email messages, pictures, digital audio, and video: XDM, for example, provides a data model for XML documents.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] The main aim of data models is to support the development of information systems by providing the definition and format of data.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] According to West and Fowler (1999) "if this is done consistently across systems then compatibility of data can be achieved.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] If the same data structures are used to store and access data then different applications can share data.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] The results of this are indicated above.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] However, systems and interfaces often cost more than they should, to build, operate, and maintain.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] They may also constrain the business rather than support it.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] A major cause is that the quality of the data models implemented in systems and interfaces is poor".
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] The reason for these problems is a lack of standards that will ensure that data models will both meet business needs and be consistent.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] A data model explicitly determines the structure of data.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Typical applications of data models include database models, design of information systems, and enabling exchange of data.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Logical data model: describes the semantics, as represented by a particular data manipulation technology.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] This consists of descriptions of tables and columns, object oriented classes, and XML tags, among other things.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Physical data model: describes the physical means by which data are stored.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] This is concerned with partitions, CPUs, tablespaces, and the like.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] The significance of this approach, according to ANSI, is that it allows the three perspectives to be relatively independent of each other.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Storage technology can change without affecting either the logical or the conceptual model.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] The table/column structure can change without (necessarily) affecting the conceptual model.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] In each case, of course, the structures must remain consistent with the other model.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] The table/column structure may be different from a direct translation of the entity classes and attributes, but it must ultimately carry out the objectives of the conceptual entity class structure.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Early phases of many software development projects emphasize the design of a conceptual data model.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Such a design can be detailed into a logical data model.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] In later stages, this model may be translated into physical data model.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] However, it is also possible to implement a conceptual model directly.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] One of the earliest pioneering works in modeling information systems was done by Young and Kent (1958), who argued for "a precise and abstract way of specifying the informational and time characteristics of a data processing problem".
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] They wanted to create "a notation that should enable the analyst to organize the problem around any piece of hardware".
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Their work was the first effort to create an abstract specification and invariant basis for designing different alternative implementations using different hardware components.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] The next step in IS modeling was taken by CODASYL, an IT industry consortium formed in 1959, who essentially aimed at the same thing as Young and Kent: the development of "a proper structure for machine-independent problem definition language, at the system level of data processing".
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] This led to the development of a specific IS information algebra.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] In the 1960s data modeling gained more significance with the initiation of the management information system (MIS) concept.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] According to Leondes (2002), "during that time, the information system provided the data and information for management purposes.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] The first generation database system, called Integrated Data Store (IDS), was designed by Charles Bachman at General Electric.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Two famous database models, the network data model and the hierarchical data model, were proposed during this period of time".
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Codd worked out his theories of data arrangement, and proposed the relational model for database management based on first-order predicate logic.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] In the 1970s entity–relationship modeling emerged as a new type of conceptual data modeling, originally formalized in 1976 by Peter Chen.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Entity–relationship models were being used in the first stage of information system design during the requirements analysis to describe information needs or the type of information that is to be stored in a database.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] This technique can describe any ontology, i.e., an overview and classification of concepts and their relationships, for a certain area of interest.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Nijssen developed "Natural Language Information Analysis Method" (NIAM) method, and developed this in the 1980s in cooperation with Terry Halpin into Object–Role Modeling (ORM).
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] However, it was Terry Halpin's 1989 PhD thesis that created the formal foundation on which Object–Role Modeling is based.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Bill Kent, in his 1978 book *Data and Reality,* compared a data model to a map of a territory, emphasizing that in the real world, "highways are not painted red, rivers don't have county lines running down the middle, and you can't see contour lines on a mountain".
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] In contrast to other researchers who tried to create models that were mathematically clean and elegant, Kent emphasized the essential messiness of the real world, and the task of the data modeler to create order out of chaos without excessively distorting the truth.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Harrington (2000), "the development of the object-oriented paradigm brought about a fundamental change in the way we look at data and the procedures that operate on data.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Traditionally, data and procedures have been stored separately: the data and their relationship in a database, the procedures in an application program.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] During the early 1990s, three Dutch mathematicians Guido Bakema, Harm van der Lek, and JanPieter Zwart, continued the development on the work of G.M.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] They focused more on the communication part of the semantics.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] In 1997 they formalized the method Fully Communication Oriented Information Modeling FCO-IM.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] A database model is a specification describing how a database is structured and used.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Several such models have been suggested.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] This may not strictly qualify as a data model.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] The flat (or table) model consists of a single, two-dimensional array of data elements, where all members of a given column are assumed to be similar values, and all members of a row are assumed to be related to one another.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] The hierarchical model is similar to the network model except that links in the hierarchical model form a tree structure, while the network model allows arbitrary graph.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] , organizes data using two fundamental constructs, called records and sets.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Records (or nodes) contain fields (i.e. attributes), and sets (or edges) define one-to-many, many-to-many and many-to-one relationships between records: one owner, many members.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] The network data model is an abstraction of the design concept used in the implementation of databases.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Network models emphasise interconnectedness, making them ideal for applications where relationships are crucial, like social networks or recommendation systems.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] This structure allows for efficient querying of relationships without expensive joins.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] is a database model based on first-order predicate logic.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Its core idea is to describe a database as a collection of predicates over a finite set of predicate variables, describing constraints on the possible values and combinations of values.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] The power of the relational data model lies in its mathematical foundations and a simple user-level paradigm.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] A method of data modeling that has been defined as "attribute free", and "fact-based".
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] The result is a verifiably correct system, from which other common artifacts, such as ERD, UML, and semantic models may be derived.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Associations between data objects are described during the database design procedure, such that normalization is an inevitable result of the process.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] The simplest style of data warehouse schema.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] The star schema consists of a few "fact tables" (possibly only one, justifying the name) referencing any number of "dimension tables".
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] A data structure diagram (DSD) is a diagram and data model used to describe conceptual data models by providing graphical notations which document entities and their relationships, and the constraints that bind them.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] The basic graphic elements of DSDs are boxes, representing entities, and arrows, representing relationships.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Data structure diagrams are most useful for documenting complex data entities.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Data structure diagrams are an extension of the entity–relationship model (ER model).
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] In DSDs, attributes are specified inside the entity boxes rather than outside of them, while relationships are drawn as boxes composed of attributes which specify the constraints that bind entities together.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] DSDs differ from the ER model in that the ER model focuses on the relationships between different entities, whereas DSDs focus on the relationships of the elements within an entity and enable users to fully see the links and relationships between each entity.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] There are several styles for representing data structure diagrams, with the notable difference in the manner of defining cardinality.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] The choices are between arrow heads, inverted arrow heads (crow's feet), or numerical representation of the cardinality.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] An entity–relationship model (ERM), sometimes referred to as an entity–relationship diagram (ERD), could be used to represent an abstract conceptual data model (or semantic data model or physical data model) used in software engineering to represent structured data.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] There are several notations used for ERMs.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Like DSD's, attributes are specified inside the entity boxes rather than outside of them, while relationships are drawn as lines, with the relationship constraints as descriptions on the line.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] The E-R model, while robust, can become visually cumbersome when representing entities with several attributes.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] There are several styles for representing data structure diagrams, with a notable difference in the manner of defining cardinality.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] A data model in Geographic information systems is a mathematical construct for representing geographic objects or surfaces as data.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Generic data models are generalizations of conventional data models.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] They define standardized general relation types, together with the kinds of things that may be related by such a relation type.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Generic data models are developed as an approach to solving some shortcomings of conventional data models.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] For example, different modelers usually produce different conventional data models of the same domain.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] This can lead to difficulty in bringing the models of different people together and is an obstacle for data exchange and data integration.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Invariably, however, this difference is attributable to different levels of abstraction in the models and differences in the kinds of facts that can be instantiated (the semantic expression capabilities of the models).
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] The modelers need to communicate and agree on certain elements that are to be rendered more concretely, in order to make the differences less significant.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] A semantic data model in software engineering is a technique to define the meaning of data within the context of its interrelationships with other data.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] A semantic data model is an abstraction that defines how the stored symbols relate to the real world.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] A semantic data model is sometimes called a conceptual data model.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] The logical data structure of a database management system (DBMS), whether hierarchical, network, or relational, cannot totally satisfy the requirements for a conceptual definition of data because it is limited in scope and biased toward the implementation strategy employed by the DBMS.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Therefore, the need to define data from a conceptual view has led to the development of semantic data modeling techniques.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] That is, techniques to define the meaning of data within the context of its interrelationships with other data.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] The real world, in terms of resources, ideas, events, etc., are symbolically defined within physical data stores.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Thus, the model must be a true representation of the real world.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Data architecture is the design of data for use in defining the target state and the subsequent planning needed to hit the target state.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] It is usually one of several architecture domains that form the pillars of an enterprise architecture or solution architecture.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] A data architecture describes the data structures used by a business and/or its applications.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] There are descriptions of data in storage and data in motion; descriptions of data stores, data groups, and data items; and mappings of those data artifacts to data qualities, applications, locations, etc.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Essential to realizing the target state, Data architecture describes how data is processed, stored, and utilized in a given system.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] It provides criteria for data processing operations that make it possible to design data flows and also control the flow of data in the system.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Data modeling in software engineering is the process of creating a data model by applying formal data model descriptions using data modeling techniques.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Data modeling is a technique for defining business requirements for a database.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] It is sometimes called *database modeling* because a data model is eventually implemented in a database.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] The figure illustrates the way data models are developed and used today.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] A conceptual data model is developed based on the data requirements for the application that is being developed, perhaps in the context of an activity model.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] The data model will normally consist of entity types, attributes, relationships, integrity rules, and the definitions of those objects.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] This is then used as the start point for interface or database design.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Another kind of data model describes how to organize data using a database management system or other data management technology.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] It describes, for example, relational tables and columns or object-oriented classes and attributes.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Such a data model is sometimes referred to as the *physical data model*, but in the original ANSI three schema architecture, it is called "logical".
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] In that architecture, the physical model describes the storage media (cylinders, tracks, and tablespaces).
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Ideally, this model is derived from the more conceptual data model described above.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] It may differ, however, to account for constraints like processing capacity and usage patterns.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] A different approach is to use adaptive systems such as artificial neural networks that can autonomously create implicit models of data.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] A data structure is a way of storing data in a computer so that it can be used efficiently.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] It is an organization of mathematical and logical concepts of data.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Often a carefully chosen data structure will allow the most efficient algorithm to be used.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] The choice of the data structure often begins from the choice of an abstract data type.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] A data model describes the structure of the data within a given domain and, by implication, the underlying structure of that domain itself.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] This means that a data model in fact specifies a dedicated *grammar* for a dedicated artificial language for that domain.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] A data model represents classes of entities (kinds of things) about which a company wishes to hold information, the attributes of that information, and relationships among those entities and (often implicit) relationships among those attributes.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] The model describes the organization of the data to some extent irrespective of how data might be represented in a computer system.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] The entities represented by a data model can be the tangible entities, but models that include such concrete entity classes tend to change over time.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Robust data models often identify abstractions of such entities.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] For example, a data model might include an entity class called "Person", representing all the people who interact with an organization.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Such an abstract entity class is typically more appropriate than ones called "Vendor" or "Employee", which identify specific roles played by those people.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] A data model *instance*, i.e. applying a data model *theory* to create a practical data model *instance* for some particular application.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] For example, in the relational model, the structural part is based on a modified concept of the mathematical relation; the integrity part is expressed in first-order logic and the manipulation part is expressed using the relational algebra, tuple calculus and domain calculus.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] A data model instance is created by applying a data model theory.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] This is typically done to solve some business enterprise requirement.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Business requirements are normally captured by a semantic logical data model.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] This is transformed into a physical data model instance from which is generated a physical database.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] For example, a data modeler may use a data modeling tool to create an entity–relationship model of the corporate data repository of some business enterprise.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] This model is transformed into a relational model, which in turn generates a relational database.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Patterns are common data modeling structures that occur in many data models.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] A data-flow diagram (DFD) is a graphical representation of the "flow" of data through an information system.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] It differs from the flowchart as it shows the *data* flow instead of the *control* flow of the program.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] A data-flow diagram can also be used for the visualization of data processing (structured design).
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Data-flow diagrams were invented by Larry Constantine, the original developer of structured design, based on Martin and Estrin's "data-flow graph" model of computation.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] It is common practice to draw a context-level data-flow diagram first which shows the interaction between the system and outside entities.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] The **DFD** is designed to show how a system is divided into smaller portions and to highlight the flow of data between those parts.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] An Information model is not a type of data model, but more or less an alternative model.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Within the field of software engineering, both a data model and an information model can be abstract, formal representations of entity types that include their properties, relationships and the operations that can be performed on them.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] The entity types in the model may be kinds of real-world objects, such as devices in a network, or they may themselves be abstract, such as for the entities used in a billing system.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Typically, they are used to model a constrained domain that can be described by a closed set of entity types, properties, relationships and operations.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] According to Lee (1999) an information model is a representation of concepts, relationships, constraints, rules, and operations to specify data semantics for a chosen domain of discourse.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] It can provide sharable, stable, and organized structure of information requirements for the domain context.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] More in general the term *information model* is used for models of individual things, such as facilities, buildings, process plants, etc.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] In those cases the concept is specialised to Facility Information Model, Building Information Model, Plant Information Model, etc.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Such an information model is an integration of a model of the facility with the data and documents about the facility.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] An information model provides formalism to the description of a problem domain without constraining how that description is mapped to an actual implementation in software.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] There may be many mappings of the information model.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Such mappings are called data models, irrespective of whether they are object models (e.g. using UML), entity–relationship models or XML schemas.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] An object model in computer science is a collection of objects or classes through which a program can examine and manipulate some specific parts of its world.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] In other words, the object-oriented interface to some service or system.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Such an interface is said to be the *object model of* the represented service or system.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] For example, the Document Object Model (DOM) is a collection of objects that represent a page in a web browser, used by script programs to examine and dynamically change the page.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] There is a Microsoft Excel object model for controlling Microsoft Excel from another program, and the ASCOM Telescope Driver is an object model for controlling an astronomical telescope.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] In computing the term *object model* has a distinct second meaning of the general properties of objects in a specific computer programming language, technology, notation or methodology that uses them.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] For example, the *Java object model*, the *COM object model*, or *the object model of OMT*.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Such object models are usually defined using concepts such as class, message, inheritance, polymorphism, and encapsulation.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] There is an extensive literature on formalized object models as a subset of the formal semantics of programming languages.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Object–Role Modeling (ORM) is a method for conceptual modeling, and can be used as a tool for information and rules analysis.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] Object–Role Modeling is a fact-oriented method for performing systems analysis at the conceptual level.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] The quality of a database application depends critically on its design.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] To help ensure correctness, clarity, adaptability and productivity, information systems are best specified first at the conceptual level, using concepts and language that people can readily understand.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] The conceptual design may include data, process and behavioral perspectives, and the actual DBMS used to implement the design might be based on one of many logical data models (relational, hierarchic, network, object-oriented, etc.).
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] The Unified Modeling Language (UML) is a standardized general-purpose modeling language in the field of software engineering.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] It is a graphical language for visualizing, specifying, constructing, and documenting the artifacts of a software-intensive system.
[src:pyarrow-python/data-model] UML offers a mix of functional models, data models, and database models.
[src:pyarrow-python/getstarted] Arrow manages data in arrays (`pyarrow.Array`), which can be grouped in tables (`pyarrow.Table`) to represent columns of data in tabular data.
[src:pyarrow-python/getstarted] Arrow also provides support for various formats to get those tabular data in and out of disk and networks.
[src:pyarrow-python/getstarted] Most commonly used formats are Parquet (Reading and Writing the Apache Parquet Format) and the IPC format (Streaming, Serialization, and IPC).
[src:pyarrow-python/getstarted] Arrays in Arrow are collections of data of uniform type.
[src:pyarrow-python/getstarted] That allows Arrow to use the best performing implementation to store the data and perform computations on it.
[src:pyarrow-python/getstarted] See Data Types and In-Memory Data Model for more details.
[src:pyarrow-python/getstarted] Saving and loading back data in arrow is usually done through Parquet, IPC format (Feather File Format), CSV or Line-Delimited JSON formats.
[src:pyarrow-python/getstarted] See Compute Functions for a list of available compute functions and how to use them.
[src:pyarrow-python/getstarted] For further details on how to work with big datasets, how to filter them, how to project them, etc., refer to Tabular Datasets documentation.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-csv] Arrow supports reading and writing columnar data from/to CSV files.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-csv] CSV reading and writing functionality is available through the `pyarrow.csv` module.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-csv] The writer does not yet support all Arrow types.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-csv] To assign a column as `duration`, the CSV values must be numeric strings that match the expected unit (e.g.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-csv] For memory-constrained environments, it is also possible to read a CSV file one batch at a time, using `open_csv()`.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-csv] Type inference is done on the first block and types are frozen afterwards; to make sure the right data types are inferred, either set `ReadOptions.block_size` to a large enough value, or use `ConvertOptions.column_types` to set the desired data types explicitly.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-csv] By default, CSV files are expected to be encoded in UTF8.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-csv] Non-UTF8 data is accepted for `binary` columns.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-csv] To write CSV files one batch at a time, create a `CSVWriter`.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-csv] Due to the structure of CSV files, one cannot expect the same levels of performance as when reading dedicated binary formats like Parquet.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-csv] Nevertheless, Arrow strives to reduce the overhead of reading CSV files.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-csv] A reasonable expectation is at least 100 MB/s per core on a performant desktop or laptop computer (measured in source CSV bytes, not target Arrow data bytes).
[src:pyarrow-python/python-csv] Performance options can be controlled through the `ReadOptions` class.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-csv] Multi-threaded reading is the default for highest performance, distributing the workload efficiently over all available cores.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-csv] The number of concurrent threads is automatically inferred by Arrow.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-csv] You can inspect and change it using the `cpu_count()` and `set_cpu_count()` functions, respectively.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-data] Apache Arrow defines columnar array data structures by composing type metadata with memory buffers, like the ones explained in the documentation on Memory and IO.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-data] We will examine these in the sections below in a series of examples.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-data] The `Schema` type is similar to the `struct` array type; it defines the column names and types in a record batch or table data structure.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-data] In some applications, you may not create schemas directly, only using the ones that are embedded in IPC messages.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-data] Schemas are immutable, which means you can’t update an existing schema, but you can create a new one with updated values using `Schema.set()`.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-data] For each data type, there is an accompanying array data structure for holding memory buffers that define a single contiguous chunk of columnar array data.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-data] When you are using PyArrow, this data may come from IPC tools, though it can also be created from various types of Python sequences (lists, NumPy arrays, pandas data).
[src:pyarrow-python/python-data] A simple way to create arrays is with `pyarrow.array`, which is similar to the `numpy.array` function.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-data] Scalar values can be selected with normal indexing.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-data] Arrow data is immutable, so values can be selected but not assigned.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-data] As mentioned in the above section, the Python object `None` is always converted to an Arrow null element on the conversion to `pyarrow.Array`.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-data] For the float NaN value which is either represented by the Python object `float('nan')` or `numpy.nan` we normally convert it to a *valid* float value during the conversion.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-data] If an integer input is supplied to `pyarrow.array` that contains `np.nan`, `ValueError` is raised.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-data] To handle better compatibility with Pandas, we support interpreting NaN values as null elements.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-data] This is enabled automatically on all `from_pandas` function and can be enabled on the other conversion functions by passing `from_pandas=True` as a function parameter.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-data] ListView arrays have a different set of buffers than List arrays.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-data] The ListView array has both an offsets and sizes buffer, while a List array only has an offsets buffer.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-data] See the format specification for more details on ListView Layout.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-data] Struct arrays can be initialized from a sequence of Python dicts or tuples.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-data] When initializing a struct array, nulls are allowed both at the struct level and at the individual field level.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-data] You can also construct a struct array from existing arrays for each of the struct’s components.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-data] MapArrays can also be constructed from offset, key, and item arrays.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-data] Offsets represent the starting position of each map.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-data] Note that the `MapArray.keys` and `MapArray.items` properties give the *flattened* keys and items.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-data] To keep the keys and items associated to their row, use the `ListArray.from_arrays()` constructor with the `MapArray.offsets` property.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-data] The union type represents a nested array type where each value can be one (and only one) of a set of possible types.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-data] There are two possible storage types for union arrays: sparse and dense.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-data] In a sparse union array, each of the child arrays has the same length as the resulting union array.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-data] The **Dictionary** type in PyArrow is a special array type that is similar to a factor in R or a `pandas.Categorical`.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-data] It enables one or more record batches in a file or stream to transmit integer *indices* referencing a shared **dictionary** containing the distinct values in the logical array.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-data] This is particularly often used with strings to save memory and improve performance.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-data] The way that dictionaries are handled in the Apache Arrow format and the way they appear in C++ and Python is slightly different.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-data] We define a special `DictionaryArray` type with a corresponding dictionary type.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-data] A **Record Batch** in Apache Arrow is a collection of equal-length array instances.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-data] The PyArrow `Table` type is not part of the Apache Arrow specification, but is rather a tool to help with wrangling multiple record batches and array pieces as a single logical dataset.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-data] As a relevant example, we may receive multiple small record batches in a socket stream, then need to concatenate them into contiguous memory for use in NumPy or pandas.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-data] The Table object makes this efficient without requiring additional memory copying.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-data] The table’s columns are instances of `ChunkedArray`, which is a container for one or more arrays of the same type.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-data] This is similar to `Table.from_batches`, but uses tables as input instead of record batches.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-data] Record batches can be made into tables, but not the other way around, so if your data is already in table form, then use `pyarrow.concat_tables`.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-data] Many functions in PyArrow either return or take as an argument a `RecordBatchReader`.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-data] It can be used like any iterable of record batches, but also provides their common schema without having to get any of the batches.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-data] It can also be sent between languages using the C stream interface.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-data] Each array of the `RecordBatch` has it’s own contiguous memory that is not necessarily adjacent to other arrays.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-data] A different memory structure that is used in machine learning libraries is a two dimensional array (also called a 2-dim tensor or a matrix) which takes only one contiguous block of memory.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-data] For this reason there is a function `pyarrow.RecordBatch.to_tensor()` available to efficiently convert tabular columnar data into a tensor.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-data] Data types supported in this conversion are unsigned, signed integer and float types.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-data] Currently only column-major conversion is supported.
[src:pyarrow-python/python-data] With `null_to_nan` set to `True` one can also convert data with nulls.
